May 22 at 9:09 PM ¬∑

The highest honor that an FFA member can earn from their state association is the State FFA Degree.

It‚Äôs many hours of hard work, planning ahead and focusing on the end goal. It also includes learning to navigate a fairly unique (and sometimes challenging!) record-keeping system, completing an assessment and interview process, and participating in a wide variety of community service programming and FFA activities at the chapter, district, state and national levels.

Members who earn this degree receive a golden key to wear on their degree chain, and stay on track to earning the highest possible honor that the FFA organization can bestow, the American FFA Degree. Recipients also receive a free year‚Äôs membership to the Nebraska FFA Alumni group!

Congratulations to Nadia Campbell for earning the Nebraska FFA State Degree!!

KNOP-TV News 2 with Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Nebraska.
Paid Partnership ¬∑

Look at what a teacher at Medicine Valley Elementary School In Curtis did for her six and seven-year old students today for May Day! So awesome. Mrs. Kristi Evans is one of our EVERYDAY HEROES today being featured on the news.

Kristi went 150 miles traveling around delivering the May Day baskets to her students. It‚Äôs a perfect holiday for social distancing (minus the kids if you get caught!!!) She said it‚Äôs the blessing she chooses to find - that she had time to remember the holiday!

Thank you Mrs. Evans! Your kids are lucky to have you!

If you have. EVERYDAY HERO you‚Äôd like to recognize - go to the NEWS 2 app or website and go to the Upload Photos and Video button and look for the EVERYDAY HEROES ALBUM! It‚Äôs that easy. Send a picture or video and it might make it on air!

#TrueBlueHeroes

post_text:
~A DAY IN THE LIFE OF COVID-19 E-LEARNING~
"Art class is one of the things that I miss the most about not being able to be in school anymore. So I have been keeping myself busy by working on my projects that I started while we were still in school. Being able to finish them and still continue to work on my art at my house has been one of the small blessings that has came with not being in school. It is a difficult process sometimes, but being able to communicate with my art teacher, Mr. Chapman, through email has been very useful. After finishing my other school work, it is super fun to be able to work on my projects and continue with my art."
- Senior, Hannah Schultz
#raiderstrong

Molly Clayton
March 22 at 12:21 PM ¬∑

I had seen the post about the bear hunt, but didnt think much about it until this morning. We took a ride around town because Lucy is a little stir crazy. When I saw the first bear, I almost ran off the road! I was so excited. The kids were thrilled!
For those who havent seen, it's based on the children's book "going on a bear hunt". The idea is to put a bear in your window, and parents can drive the children around on a bear hunt. If you live in Iota, please consider putting a bear in a window ‚ù§. We will go bear hunting again this week!

Attention K-4th Grade Parents: Assignment Packets for next week and some text books will be available for pickup at the elementary building on Thursday March 26th, from 11:00 a.m. till 1:00 p.m. The packets will be in rows according to each class and labeled with each students name in front of the building.

5th and 6th Grade packets have already been mailed.

In accordance with social distancing we ask that there be NO congregating on the school grounds and only ADULTS may pick up the packets. Staff will not be available to talk to you, but will be supervising the pickups.

Due to concerns regarding COVID-19 and a commitment to keep the over 1,300 registered students and advisers from 90 Nebraska communities safe, the Nebraska Department of Education has made the decision to cancel all large group gatherings, in-person meetings and the Nebraska FCCLA State Leadership Conference scheduled for April 5-7 in Lincoln. Additional information will be shared via the FCCLA adviser listserv, Nebraska FCCLA website and social media channels when available. Please email Kristin Vest, State Adviser with any questions or concerns.

A big congratulations to our DISTRICT CHAMPION Poultry Management team!

These 4 competed today against 9 other teams (30 individuals) and came out on top by 3 points.

The competition includes a written exam, grading the interior quality of eggs, grading the exterior quality of eggs, identification of carcass parts, judging various processed poultry products and placing classes of poultry products.

Quade W Potter placed 2nd overall, Nadia Campbell finished one 3rd overall, Brianna Marie Taylor was in 9th place and Jaden Henderson finished in 23rd place.
